[normal]Mr Mascherini[bold]: I can start.
[normal] 
[normal]The concept of the Youth Guarantee was born in Scandinavian countries in the 1980s and is based on the concept that young people are guaranteed an opp
[normal]ortunity a certain amount of time after
[normal] becoming unemployed or finishing their education.
[normal] 
[normal]At the European level the discussion about
[normal] the
[normal] Youth Guarantee started in 2005 when the European Council encouraged member state
[normal]s to guarantee an opportunity for
[normal] young 
[normal]people four months after
[normal] becoming unemployed.
[normal]The discussion has gone on for years and the European Pa
[normal]rliament realised the need to guarantee an opportunity for young people. 
[normal]In December 2012 the European Commission 
[normal]made a proposal for a youth guarantee
[normal] to the European Council.
[normal] 
[normal]That has been endorsed and published by the European Council on 22 April.
[normal] On the basis of the European C
[normal]ouncil recommendation, the guarantee is that every young person
[normal] has to receive an opportunity four months after
[normal] becoming unemployed or finishing educati
[normal]on
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]That can be an educational position, a study place, an apprenticeship, an internship, training or
[normal] an offer of
[normal] a job within four months.
[normal] 
[normal]This happened last April.
[normal] 
[normal]Now member states are required to submit an implementation plan for the Youth Guarantee.
[normal] 
[normal]The deadline is December 2013 for those member states that have a
[normal]n un
[normal]employment rate higher than 25%;
[normal] otherwise it is spring 2014 for the other member states.
[normal] 
[normal]The level of unemployment below or above 25% is the condition for accessing funding.
[normal] 
[normal]In this regard, €6 billion has been made available for those re
[normal]gions whose un
[normal]employment rates are
[normal] above 25%.
[normal] 
[normal]This is linked to the submission of the implementation plan to the European Commission.
[normal] 
[normal]This is the status, I would say. 
